    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(structuredData)}></script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <main class="page">
      <header class="hero">
        <div class="site-tools">
          <a class="home-link" href="/" aria-label="Back to home">sokolsky.me</a>
        </div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Argentina · Economy · 1990–2026</p>
        <h1>{pageTitle}</h1>
        <p class="dek">
          What the IMF's own post-mortems and free-market economists actually blame, where they disagree with each other and which popular explanations don't survive contact with the data.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article">
        <section id="overview" aria-labelledby="overview-heading">
          <h2 id="overview-heading">Overview</h2>
          <p>
            Argentina's GDP per capita did grow after 1990. In constant 2021 PPP dollars it rose from about <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.PP.KD?locations=AR" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">$17,000 to $26,800</a> over 1990–2024, a 57% gain. That sounds respectable until you annualize it (1.34% a year) and compare it with plausible peers over the same window: Uruguay grew about 128%, Chile 176% and Poland 252%. Worse, all of Argentina's net progress happened before 2011. The <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.KD?locations=AR" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">World Bank series</a> in constant 2015 dollars peaked at $14,041 in 2011 and stood at $12,774 in 2024, 9% below the peak. The IMF's <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2026/english/1argea2026001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2026 Article IV consultation</a> puts the 2011-2024 decline at close to 15%, using a different national-accounts vintage. The estimates differ, but both show more than a decade without lasting per-capita growth in a country that ranked among the world's ten richest around 1913.
          </p>
          <p>
            The 2007-2015 data are less reliable because Argentina falsified its official statistics. After Néstor Kirchner replaced senior INDEC staff in early 2007, official inflation ran at a fraction of private estimates (<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-02-01/argentina-becomes-first-nation-censured-by-imf-on-inflation-data" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">10.8% versus 25.6%</a> in 2011) and GDP was overstated accordingly. In February 2013 the IMF issued a <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/news/articles/2015/09/14/01/49/pr1333" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">declaration of censure</a> against Argentina, the first in the Fund's history. It <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2016/11/09/PR16497-Argentina-IMF-Executive-Board-Removes-Declaration-of-Censure" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">lifted the censure</a> in November 2016 after the statistics agency was rebuilt. Treat figures from that window cautiously.
          </p>
          <figure class="gdp-chart">
            <div class="chart-heading">
              <div>
                <p class="chart-kicker">The dollar-value roller coaster</p>
                <h3>GDP per person, current US dollars</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="chart-unit">1990–2025 · ARKLEMS + parallel-FX adjusted</p>
            </div>
            <svg
              viewBox={`0 0 ${chart.width} ${chart.height}`}
              role="img"
              aria-labelledby="gdp-chart-title gdp-chart-desc"
            >
              <title id="gdp-chart-title">Argentina GDP per capita in current US dollars, 1990 to 2025</title>
              <desc id="gdp-chart-desc">Adjusted series chains ARKLEMS real GDP growth at 1.8 percent a year for 2007 through 2015 and deflates cepo-era dollar values with parallel-market exchange rates. Dashed line shows the World Bank revised series without those corrections. Values fall from about 4,300 dollars in 1990 to 2,570 in 2002, peak near 10,800 adjusted dollars in 2011, and reach 14,900 dollars in 2025.</desc>
              <defs>
                <linearGradient id="gdp-area" x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="1">
                  <stop offset="0%" stop-color="var(--chart-line)" stop-opacity="0.2"></stop>
                  <stop offset="100%" stop-color="var(--chart-line)" stop-opacity="0"></stop>
                </linearGradient>
              </defs>

              <rect
                class="chart-warning"
                x={xForYear(2007)}
                y={chart.top}
                width={xForYear(2015) - xForYear(2007)}
                height={plotHeight}
              ></rect>
              <text
                class="warning-label"
                x={(xForYear(2007) + xForYear(2015)) / 2}
                y={chart.top - 15}
                text-anchor="middle"
              >INDEC intervention</text>

              {yTicks.map((tick) => (
                <g>
                  <line
                    class="grid-line"
                    x1={chart.left}
                    x2={chart.width - chart.right}
                    y1={yForValue(tick)}
                    y2={yForValue(tick)}
                  ></line>
                  <text
                    class="axis-label axis-label-y"
                    x={chart.left - 12}
                    y={yForValue(tick) + 4}
                    text-anchor="end"
                  >{tick === 0 ? "$0" : `$${tick / 1000}k`}</text>
                </g>
              ))}

              {xTicks.map((tick) => (
                <text
                  class="axis-label"
                  x={xForYear(tick)}
                  y={chart.height - 17}
                  text-anchor={tick === 1990 ? "start" : tick === 2025 ? "end" : "middle"}
                >{tick}</text>
              ))}

              <path class="chart-area" d={areaPath}></path>
              <path class="chart-line chart-line-published" d={publishedLinePath}></path>
              <path class="chart-line" d={adjustedLinePath}></path>

              {chartLabels.map(([year, value]) => (
                <g class="chart-marker">
                  <circle cx={xForYear(year)} cy={yForValue(value)} r="4.5"></circle>
                  <text
                    x={xForYear(year)}
                    y={yForValue(value) - 12}
                    text-anchor={year === 1998 ? "end" : year === 2025 ? "end" : "middle"}
                    dx={year === 1998 ? -6 : year === 2025 ? -5 : 0}
                  >{formatDollars(value)}</text>
                </g>
              ))}

              <g class="chart-legend" transform={`translate(${chart.left}, ${chart.top - 34})`}>
                <line class="chart-legend-line" x1="0" x2="22" y1="6" y2="6"></line>
                <text class="chart-legend-label" x="28" y="10">Adjusted (ARKLEMS + parallel FX)</text>
                <line class="chart-legend-line chart-legend-line-published" x1="248" x2="270" y1="6" y2="6"></line>
                <text class="chart-legend-label" x="276" y="10">World Bank revised</text>
              </g>
            </svg>
            <div class="chart-reading">
              <p><strong>Real output correction:</strong> 2007–2015 values chain ARKLEMS growth (1.8% a year) from the 2006 anchor instead of the old INDEK path (3.3%). The rebuilt World Bank series already matches ARKLEMS on real GDP; this step makes that explicit.</p>
              <p><strong>Exchange-rate correction:</strong> 2011–2015 values are further scaled by the official-to-parallel peso rate during the cepo. Capital controls kept the official dollar artificially cheap, inflating dollar-denominated GDP by up to one-third.</p>
            </div>
            <figcaption>
              Adjusted series: World Bank <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.CD?locations=AR" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">NY.GDP.PCAP.CD</a> and <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.KD?locations=AR" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">NY.GDP.PCAP.KD</a> (July 1, 2026), with 2007–2015 real GDP re-chained to Ariel Coremberg's <a href="https://arklems.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/coremberg_2017_ipm.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ARKLEMS</a> 1.8% CAGR (table 2) and cepo-year dollar values deflated using documented blue-dollar premia. Dashed line: revised World Bank series without those two corrections. Values rounded to the nearest dollar.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </section>

        <section id="the-core-disease" aria-labelledby="the-core-disease-heading">
          <h2 id="the-core-disease-heading">The core disease</h2>
          <p>
            The same combination kept recurring. Governments adopted monetary or exchange-rate anchors inconsistent with fiscal policy, financed the gap by printing pesos or borrowing in dollars, resisted adjustment with controls and repeatedly changed the rules. Each crisis destroyed savings, credit, investment and productivity.
          </p>
          <p>
            The University of Chicago history, Nicolás Cachanosky, the World Bank and the IMF all put fiscal dominance near the root of the problem, though deficits alone do not explain every crisis. The <a href="https://manifold.bfi.uchicago.edu/read/case-of-argentina/section/9905ef24-8c94-42ad-adf7-068efb4d9afb" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Chicago history</a> dates a structural break in Argentina's deficit behavior to 1991 (when convertibility briefly ended inflation) and notes that after 2010 inflation rose again and per-capita income stopped growing. Cachanosky puts average annual <a href="https://www.bloomberglinea.com/english/argentina-can-dollarize-in-2024-without-limiting-growth-says-nicolas-cachanosky/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">inflation since 1940</a> at 60%, punctuated by hyperinflations. The country has defaulted on its sovereign debt nine times, three of them since 2001. The <a href="https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/099061224182598390/pdf/P1749671ac038b03e1bc271505e88eab550.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">World Bank's memorandum</a> ranks macroeconomic volatility driven by procyclical fiscal policy as the first of three binding constraints on growth, ahead of restrictive trade policy and declining human capital. The <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2022/english/1argea2022001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IMF's 2022 program</a> treated ending monetary financing of the deficit as the precondition for everything else.
          </p>
          <p>
            Vito Tanzi, who led the IMF's fiscal department and spent decades on Argentine missions, frames the same problem as a <strong>permanent fiscal disequilibrium</strong>: legislatively mandated spending tends to exceed the revenue citizens will tolerate and administrations can collect under normal conditions. Equilibrium is restored only through exceptional tax drives or unsustainable spending cuts—delayed supplier payments, collapsed public investment, real wage compression—that eventually reverse. In his memoir <cite>Argentina: An Economic Chronicle</cite> (2007) he traces the template to the first Perón government (1946–1955), when commodity rents financed a welfare expansion that pushed public spending to roughly 30% of GDP, an unusually high share for the era. That is memoir, not audited history, but the structural point matches the data: Argentina keeps legislating benefits it does not reliably fund.
          </p>
          <p>
            High inflation makes the gap worse through the mechanism Tanzi formalized in his <a href="https://ideas.repec.org/a/pal/imfstp/v24y1977i1p154-167.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">1977 IMF paper</a>, now called the <strong>Tanzi effect</strong>: collection lags mean tax receipts are assessed on past nominal bases while prices have already risen, so real revenue falls unless brackets and assessments are indexed instantly. Inflation therefore both signals and deepens fiscal stress—a feedback loop the military government confronted when the deficit reached about <a href="https://www.minneapolisfed.org/research/sr/sr580.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">11% of GDP</a> in 1975 (Tanzi, on the scene, recalls figures closer to 14% and tax ratios as low as 8% at the center and 12% for the whole public sector). Disinflation later works in reverse, which is one reason convertibility's early years felt fiscally easier than they were.
          </p>
          <p>
            The damage compounds through finance. Because the peso cannot be trusted, Argentines hold well over $200 billion in physical dollars and offshore accounts; domestic credit to the private sector is <a href="https://www.cato.org/free-society/fall-2025/liberty-versus-power-mileis-argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">about 15% of GDP</a>, versus 71% in Brazil, 109% in Chile and 192% in the United States. Firms that cannot borrow cannot invest, whatever the tax code says.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="seven-episodes-seven-verdicts" aria-labelledby="seven-episodes-seven-verdicts-heading">
          <h2 id="seven-episodes-seven-verdicts-heading">Seven episodes, seven verdicts</h2>
          <h3 id="1991-1997-stabilization-that-worked">1991-1997: stabilization that worked</h3>
          <p>
            The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convertibility_plan" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Convertibility Plan</a> of April 1991 pegged the peso 1:1 to the dollar with (mostly) full reserve backing. It killed hyperinflation dead and, together with privatization, deregulation and trade opening, produced <a href="https://www.imf.org/external/np/ieo/2003/arg/index.htm" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">average growth near 6%</a> through 1997. Calling this period an unqualified neoliberal failure is simply false. The mistake was believing early stabilization had permanently solved the fiscal, debt and institutional problems underneath. Tanzi's later reconstruction is sharper: through the mid-1990s, exceptional revenue—proceeds from the 1989 tax reform, the Tanzi effect running in reverse as inflation fell, privatization receipts and very fast growth—masked a structural gap between rising real spending and ordinary tax collection. When those windfalls faded after 1994, the underlying disequilibrium reappeared.
          </p>
          <p>
            The boom also created surprisingly few jobs. After the 1995 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexican_peso_crisis" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">“tequila” shock</a> GDP fell 2.8%, but even in the good years unemployment stayed elevated because privatized firms shed on the order of <a href="https://depeco.econo.unlp.edu.ar/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/semi300503.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">40% of their workforces</a> and rigid labor rules plus heavy payroll taxes limited hiring elsewhere. Tanzi, visiting Patagonia in 1994, saw the same dichotomy at the regional level: extraordinary natural wealth alongside towns cut off when privatized railroads trimmed service. Growth was real; it was not broadly shared in employment.
          </p>
          <h3 id="1998-2002-a-doomed-regime-defended-too-long">1998-2002: a doomed regime defended too long</h3>
          <p>
            The peg removed the exchange rate as a shock absorber just as the shocks arrived: a strong dollar, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samba_effect" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Brazil's 1999 devaluation</a> and the post-1998 emerging-market sudden stop. <a href="https://users.nber.org/~confer/2002/argentina02/velasco2.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Hausmann and Velasco</a> estimated the peso was overvalued by 40% or more by 2001, while dollar-denominated public and private debt meant devaluation would detonate balance sheets. They also showed that primary spending as a share of GDP did not balloon over 1993-2001. The fiscal rot came from provincial deficits, rising interest costs and the debt-financed <a href="#the-1994-pension-privatization">pension transition</a> explained below. Headline deficits nonetheless understated the strain. Mario Teijeiro's accrual reconstruction, later cited by Damill and Frenkel, found that judicially ordered spending, bond-financed arrears (“bocones”) and privatization treated as revenue could widen the true gap by roughly <a href="https://www.elibrary.imf.org/display/book/9781589063594/ch002.xml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">two percentage points</a> of GDP in some convertibility years—consistent with the IMF's own retrospective on persistent off-budget spending.
          </p>
          <p>
            Solvency, not just liquidity, was the issue. Exports remained a narrow base—about <a href="https://www.fondad.org/uploaded/Argentina/Fondad-Argentina-Chapter6.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">9% of GDP</a> by 2000, up from roughly 6% in the early 1990s—while dollar debt and interest absorbed a rising share of revenue. In February 1998 the IMF approved a precautionary <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/news/articles/2015/09/14/01/49/pr9801" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Extended Fund Facility</a> meant to contain contagion from the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Asian_financial_crisis" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Asian financial crisis</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_Russian_financial_crisis" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Russia's 1998 crisis</a>; Argentina drew only when pressured. Tanzi, then still at the Fund, argued the framing was wrong: if the problem were mere illiquidity, precautionary credit would suffice, but spending was already outpacing ordinary revenue and the gap was being rolled forward with progressively expensive foreign borrowing—including, by the late 1990s, campaign-season increases Tanzi warned about in November 1999. During the 1998–2002 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998%E2%80%932002_Argentine_great_depression" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Argentine great depression</a>, GDP per capita fell 22%, poverty passed 50% and Argentina defaulted on roughly $100 billion, then the largest default in history. The IEO's verdict on the Fund itself was blunt: it "erred by supporting inadequate policies too long" and committed up to $22 billion from late 2000 to defend a peg its own staff increasingly knew was unsustainable, with no contingency plan for exit.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2003-2011-the-boom-that-bought-nothing-durable">2003-2011: the boom that bought nothing durable</h3>
          <p>
            Recovery was fast (8-9% growth a year through 2007) thanks to idle capacity, a cheap peso and the commodity supercycle. The failure was converting none of it into institutions: no stabilization fund, no structural surplus, no independent central bank, no deep peso capital market. Chile and Norway built savings mechanisms in the same boom; Argentina built energy subsidies, export taxes of up to 35% on soy and reversed the <a href="#the-1994-pension-privatization">private pension pillar</a> in 2008. Statistics falsification began in 2007. When prices turned, the spending commitments stayed and the revenues left.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2011-2015-controls-instead-of-correction">2011-2015: controls instead of correction</h3>
          <p>
            Rather than fix the widening deficit, the government <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renationalization_of_YPF" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">expropriated 51% of YPF</a> from Repsol (2012), imposed capital controls (the cepo, November 2011), ran multiple exchange rates, capped prices and rationed imports through the DJAI licensing system. About 30% of applications, covering 36.5% of requested import value, <a href="https://www.nber.org/system/files/working_papers/w32037/w32037.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">were simply denied</a>; an NBER study estimates the restrictions raised importers' input prices by around 4%. Stagnation set in. The 2014 <i>pari passu</i> ruling and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentine_debt_restructuring" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">technical default</a> in the NML holdout litigation prolonged Argentina's exile from credit markets.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2015-2019-liberalization-financed-the-riskiest-way-possible">2015-2019: liberalization, financed the riskiest way possible</h3>
          <p>
            Macri lifted the cepo, cut export taxes and floated the peso, but paired those changes with fiscal gradualism and heavy external dollar borrowing. He reopened the capital account before establishing fiscal credibility, low inflation or an export base to service the debt. When the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018%E2%80%93present_Argentine_monetary_crisis" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2018 monetary crisis</a> struck, the sudden stop arrived on schedule and Argentina signed the largest <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2021/english/1argea2021001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IMF program</a> in history: $50 billion, raised to $57 billion (1,277% of quota). About $44 billion was disbursed. Only 4 of 12 reviews were ever completed.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2019-2023-back-to-the-printing-press">2019-2023: back to the printing press</h3>
          <p>
            The cepo returned in 2019, followed by a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentine_debt_restructuring" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ninth default</a> and restructuring in 2020, price controls, export bans and monetary financing that reached roughly 7% of GDP in the pandemic year. Inflation reached 211.4% in 2023, its highest rate since the tail of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_hyperinflation_in_Argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">1989–1990 hyperinflation</a>, and ran at 25.5% per month by December.
          </p>
          <h3 id="2023-2026-the-milei-test">2023-2026: the Milei test</h3>
          <p>
            Milei inherited inflation above 200%, a large fiscal and quasi-fiscal deficit, capital controls and a bankrupt central bank. He imposed an immediate fiscal adjustment, stopped monetary financing and sharply reduced inflation; after a 1.7% contraction in 2024, output grew 4.4% in 2025 and measured poverty fell steeply from its early-2024 peak. This is a real stabilization, not yet proof of sustained convergence. The promises, delivery and remaining risks are assessed in <a href="#would-milei-help">“Would Milei help?” below</a>.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="the-1994-pension-privatization" aria-labelledby="the-1994-pension-privatization-heading">
          <h2 id="the-1994-pension-privatization-heading">The 1994 pension privatization: sound diagnosis, unfunded transition</h2>
          <p>
            The system being replaced really was broken. The old pay-as-you-go scheme promised benefits it did not collect enough money to pay: contribution evasion was widespread, retirement ages were low, disability rules were loose and politically favored occupations had special early-retirement regimes. Inflation had eroded pensions below their legal promises and generated so much litigation that in 1991 the government recognized arrears worth 3.5% of GDP. A contemporary <a href="https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/280551468207251595/txt/multi-page.txt" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">World Bank account</a> estimated that honoring the old promises from contributions alone would have required an impossible payroll rate near 50%. Reform was not irrational; continuing unchanged was not an option.
          </p>
          <p>
            <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/normativa/nacional/ley-24241-639/actualizacion" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Law 24,241</a>, enacted in 1993 and effective in July 1994, created the Sistema Integrado de Jubilaciones y Pensiones. It was a mixed system, not a complete Chilean-style privatization. Employers legally contributed 16% of wages to an ANSES-run public pillar, which continued paying existing retirees, a basic pension and compensation for contributions made before the reform. Workers contributed another 11% and chose either an ANSES defined benefit or an individual funded account managed by a regulated private AFJP; the latter would finance an annuity or scheduled withdrawals after fees and disability and survivor insurance. Congress made the private option voluntary after political resistance, frustrating the government's and IMF program's original plan for a mandatory funded tier.
          </p>
          <p>
            The intended logic had three parts. Linking each worker's pension to a visible account was supposed to make evasion less attractive. Competing managers were supposed to allocate capital better than the state. And the accumulated funds were supposed to deepen domestic capital markets, raise national saving and eventually reduce the pension burden. The catch was timing: contributions moved immediately into individual accounts, while the Treasury still owed current pensions, the public basic benefit and accrued rights from the old system. Those promises were an existing implicit debt; privatization made the cash shortfall explicit. That can be managed with taxes, spending cuts or a pre-funded reserve. Argentina chose borrowing.
          </p>
          <p>
            It then enlarged the hole. The Menem government progressively discounted employer contributions, in some regions by 30-80%, to lower labor costs, and the federal government absorbed liabilities from insolvent provincial pension systems. By 2001, the <a href="https://www.elibrary.imf.org/display/book/9781589063808/ch002.xml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IMF's later reconstruction</a> put the annual revenue loss at 2.9% of GDP: 1.5 points from workers' money moving to AFJPs and 1.4 from payroll-tax cuts. Provincial liabilities added 0.9 points; lower pension spending offset an estimated 1.1. Net result: the reform and accompanying measures worsened the federal balance by <strong>at least 2.7% of GDP a year</strong> by 2001. This was not merely an accounting relabeling. Under convertibility the Treasury could not print the gap, so it issued debt; much of that debt was bought by the new pension funds. By 2001 AFJPs held about <a href="https://www.ssa.gov/policy/docs/ssb/v64n1/v64n1p115.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">70% in government bonds</a>, tying retirement savings back to the sovereign whose risk privatization was meant to escape.
          </p>
          <p>
            The social results also disappointed. The <a href="https://www.ssa.gov/policy/docs/ssb/v64n1/v64n1p115.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">active-contributor share fell</a> from about 66% in 1994 to 40% in early 2001, while <a href="https://cdi.mecon.gob.ar/bases/docelec/fd1041.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">contribution coverage fell</a> among employed people from 50.9% to 39.5% by 2004. Privatization did not cause Argentina's recession, unemployment or large informal sector, so it cannot fairly be blamed for that entire decline; it simply failed to cure non-compliance as promised. Fees were heavy too: AFJPs' <a href="https://www.ssa.gov/policy/docs/ssb/v64n1/v64n1p115.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">average variable charge</a> fell from 3.4% of earnings to 2.25%, but that still consumed a large share of an 11% worker contribution. The funded pillar did create a real pool of long-term assets. It did not create net national saving because the state borrowed to replace the diverted contributions, and it neither broadened coverage nor insulated savers from sovereign default.
          </p>
          <p>
            The experiment ended in November 2008. <a href="https://www.argentina.gob.ar/normativa/nacional/norma-148141" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Law 26,425</a> abolished the AFJP tier, moved its assets into ANSES's Sustainability Guarantee Fund and unified the system under public pay-as-you-go administration. That restored contribution cash flow to the Treasury and removed private fees, but it also converted individually managed balances into state-controlled assets and deepened doubts that Argentine property rules would survive a fiscal squeeze. The precise verdict is therefore neither “privatization failed” nor “the state stole a successful system.” A necessary pension reform was designed around optimistic assumptions, its transition was left unfunded, labor-market informality defeated its coverage promise, sovereign borrowing swallowed much of its saving benefit, and the eventual reversal imposed another abrupt change of rules.
          </p>
        </section>

