        <section id="what-the-imf-says-including-about-itself" aria-labelledby="what-the-imf-says-including-about-itself-heading">
          <h2 id="what-the-imf-says-including-about-itself-heading">What the IMF says, including about itself</h2>
          <p>
            The Fund's paper trail on Argentina is unusually self-critical, which makes it useful.
          </p>
          <p>
            The <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/websites/imf/imported-full-text-pdf/external/np/ieo/2004/arg/eng/pdf/_report.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IEO's 2004 report</a> concluded that Argentine policymakers failed to correct course early, while the Fund's surveillance missed the growing vulnerabilities and its lending propped up a dying regime. It found that the IMF did too little medium-term analysis of the peg, tolerated repeated fiscal non-compliance and had no plan for an orderly exit. It recommended stop-loss rules against escalating support for an unsustainable strategy. The resources spent defending the peg, the IEO noted, could have cushioned an earlier restructuring instead.
          </p>
          <p>
            Paul Blustein's <a href="https://www.publicaffairsbooks.com/titles/paul-blustein/and-the-money-kept-rolling-in-and-out-wall-street-the-imf-and-the-bankrupting-of-argentina/9781586485511/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">book</a>, <cite>And the Money Kept Rolling In (and Out)</cite>, based on interviews with policymakers and market participants, exposes how far the Fund's public reassurance diverged from its internal diagnosis. In late April 2001 an IMF task force judged that “the probability of a full-blown crisis” had increased and that avoiding one looked “unlikely, though not impossible.” Yet on May 21 the Fund publicly said the authorities had <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/news/articles/2015/09/29/18/03/nb0144" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">“responded promptly and effectively”</a> and released another $1.2 billion. This is not merely Blustein's characterization: the Fund's own <a href="https://www.elibrary.imf.org/display/book/9781589063808/ch003.xml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">subsequent reconstruction</a> reproduces both assessments.
          </p>
          <p>
            The final rescue made the tradeoff concrete. The August 2001 augmentation provided $5 billion immediately to shore up reserves and earmarked another $3 billion for debt operations. It did not restore confidence. The <a href="https://www.elibrary.imf.org/display/book/9781589063808/ch003.xml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IEO found</a> that the money financed capital flight and left Argentina more indebted to the Fund; the $3 billion debt window was never used as intended. Meanwhile banks were pressed into absorbing more government paper, raising public-sector exposure from <a href="https://ieo.imf.org/-/media/ieo/files/evaluations/completed/07-28-2004-report-on-the-evaluation-of-the-role-of-the-imf-in-argentina-1991-2001/07292004chap2.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">17.9% to 27.2%</a> of assets between end-2000 and end-2001. Each attempt to postpone default therefore weakened the banks that an orderly restructuring would need to survive.
          </p>
          <p>
            Tanzi's insider account, written after he left the Fund in 2000, reaches the same bottom line from the fiscal side. He thought the end was foreseeable once exceptional 1990s revenues expired and foreign debt began compounding against a still-closed export base. By 2000 the Fund had so much money at risk in Argentina that stopping disbursements would have forced immediate default, hurting both the borrower and the lender's own balance sheet; the liquidity-versus-solvency debate, he argued, obscured a simpler arithmetic. That is one official's memoir, not an IEO finding, but it fits the documented pattern of the <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/news/articles/2015/09/14/01/49/pr9801" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">1998 precautionary EFF</a> and the escalating support the IEO later condemned.
          </p>
          <p>
            The <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2021/english/1argea2021001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">ex-post evaluation</a> published in December 2021 found that the 2018 Stand-By Arrangement "did not achieve its objectives". The program treated a structural solvency problem as temporary illiquidity. It relied on optimistic official forecasts and renewed private capital inflows, ruled out both an early debt operation and temporary emergency measures to slow capital flight, underestimated short-maturity dollar debt and had no agreed plan B. Those limited crisis measures differ from the years-long cepo, which rationed access at multiple exchange rates. Argentine gradualism was financed in the riskiest possible way, and the Fund's crisis design and forecasting failed on their own terms.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Fund's assessment became more favorable after the fiscal turn, but not unqualified. Its <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2026/english/1argea2026001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2026 Article IV</a> treats the zero-deficit anchor and end of monetary financing as genuine achievements while emphasizing weak reserves, shallow finance, remaining distortions and exceptional repayment risks. The implications are assessed in <a href="#would-milei-help">the section below</a>.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="explanations-tested-against-the-evidence" aria-labelledby="explanations-tested-against-the-evidence-heading">
          <h2 id="explanations-tested-against-the-evidence-heading">Explanations tested against the evidence</h2>
          <p>
            Cato, Austrian and Chicago economists and the Argentine liberals around Milei agree that fiscal dominance, an unusable peso and the control apparatus damaged growth; Argentina ranked <a href="https://www.cato.org/blog/one-year-javier-milei" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">159th on economic freedom</a> out of 165 countries before Milei. They disagree over the monetary regime, the weight of government and which institutional failures mattered most. Foreign-ownership limits and weak farming fit the record poorly.
          </p>
          <h3 id="was-convertibility-a-real-currency-board">Was convertibility a real currency board?</h3>
          <p>
            Steve Hanke <a href="https://www.cato.org/testimony/argentinas-current-political-economic-crisis" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">argues it never was</a>: the central bank routinely sterilized reserve flows and retained discretion no orthodox board permits, so 2001 indicts Argentine central banking, not currency boards or dollarization. His factual point stands; the IMF itself calls the regime "currency-board-like". His counterfactual, that an orthodox board or full dollarization would have prevented the collapse, is unprovable and sits uneasily with the fiscal, provincial and dollar-debt problems a harder peg would not have touched. Hausmann and Velasco found the evidence that dollarization expands sustainable borrowing capacity to be mixed. Domingo Cavallo, convertibility's architect, maintains the system could have survived had provincial deficits been controlled early. Michael Mussa, the IMF's former chief economist, argued in his Peterson Institute post-mortem that the failure to run surpluses in the good years of the 1990s doomed the regime regardless.
          </p>
          <h3 id="dollarize-or-float">Dollarize or float?</h3>
          <p>
            Emilio Ocampo and Nicolás Cachanosky, whose book <cite><a href="https://www.mercatus.org/macro-musings/nicolas-cachanosky-dollarization-argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dollarization</a>: A Solution for Argentina</cite> shaped Milei's campaign, argue Argentina is "already de facto dollarized" and that only abolishing the peso (and with it the central bank) makes fiscal dominance impossible for future Peronist governments; <a href="https://fee.org/articles/can-dollarization-fix-argentina-s-inflation-problems/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Ecuador's experience</a> shows even a hostile populist could not reverse it. Ocampo traces the idea back to Milton Friedman's advice to Argentina in the 1970s. Skeptics reply that Argentina lacks the reserves to dollarize credibly and that dollarization without fiscal discipline solves nothing. In office, Milei instead chose the fiscal-surplus-and-exchange-band strategy assessed below; Ocampo left the team. Cato remains <a href="https://www.cato.org/blog/two-years-milei-reform-agenda-moves-forward-argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">openly impatient</a>: as long as the central bank exists, a future government can reflate, so the sooner Milei dollarizes the better. Other free-marketeers would rather see a clean float than a defended band, on the classic ground that fixed-but-adjustable regimes invite speculative attacks. This argument is not settled and the current regime is a compromise nobody's model prescribed.
          </p>
          <h3 id="how-much-was-big-government">How much was "big government"?</h3>
          <p>
            Ross Levine's <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2025/05/20/us-argentina-economic-policy-reversal/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">account</a>, protectionism plus politically directed finance plus monetary subordination, fits the long run. It fits 2001 less well. Hausmann and Velasco found that overvaluation, dollar liabilities, a closed economy and a sudden stop mattered more than a spending binge, and the IMF later adopted much of that analysis. Acemoglu and Robinson trace the instability further back: universal male suffrage arrived in 1912, followed by coups in 1930, 1943, 1955, 1962, 1966 and 1976 and stable democracy only since 1983. Political actors learned that rules might last no longer than one administration. Every anchor, peg, plan and program operated under that constraint.
          </p>
          <h3 id="foreign-ownership-limits">Were limits on foreign buyers an important factor?</h3>
          <p>
            Argentina restricts some foreign purchases of land, property and companies, but these formal entry barriers explain little of the growth record. Their erratic enforcement is part of the larger property-rights problem.
          </p>
          <p>
            Consider the timing. The 1990s were maximally open: YPF went to Spain's Repsol, the telecoms to Telefonica and France Telecom, the banks to Santander and BBVA. There are still <a href="https://www.state.gov/reports/2025-investment-climate-statements/argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">no restrictions</a> on foreigners buying residential or commercial real estate. The economy collapsed anyway. The notable ownership caps came later and were narrow: a 2003 law limiting foreign stakes in media and "cultural goods" companies to 30% and the <a href="https://wsclegal.com/en/more-on-the-argentina-rural-land-law-a-stand-for-sovereignty-or-the-pursuit-of-foreign-investment/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2011 Rural Land Law</a>, which capped foreign rural land at 15% of any national, provincial or municipal territory, 1,000 hectares per foreigner in the Pampas core zone and zero near borders or major water bodies. The cap bound almost nobody: when the registry the law created finished counting, foreigners held roughly 6% of rural land nationally, and only a few dozen departments out of hundreds ever <a href="https://www.bowtiedmara.io/p/update-on-the-ley-de-tierras" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">exceeded a local limit</a>. Milei's December 2023 megadecree attempted to repeal the law, but courts suspended that provision; the restriction remains in force pending a Supreme Court ruling.
          </p>
          <p>
            What actually repelled foreign capital was what happened after entry. The 2002 pesification and tariff freeze hit the mostly foreign-owned privatized utilities and made Argentina the <a href="https://legalblogs.wolterskluwer.com/arbitration-blog/aes-v-argentina-icsid-award-closing-the-chapter-on-argentinas-2001-2002-crisis-saga/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">most-sued state in ICSID</a>, with over 59 cases, nearly 6% of the institution's entire docket. Then came the pension seizure (2008), the YPF expropriation (2012, settled with Repsol for <a href="https://isds-americalatina.org/argentina_eng/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">$5.3 billion</a>) and cepo-era rules that <a href="https://www.state.gov/reports/2025-investment-climate-statements/argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">blocked dividend repatriation</a> for years at a time. Since the 2001 default, <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/BX.KLT.DINV.WD.GD.ZS?locations=AR-CL-UY" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">FDI inflows</a> have run at a fraction of Chile's or Uruguay's relative to GDP. Foreigners could buy nearly anything in Argentina; the problem was keeping it, pricing it and getting the money out. That is why Milei's flagship investment tool, the 2024 RIGI regime, offers large investors 30 years of tax, customs and FX stability rather than merely open doors. The doors were rarely the issue.
          </p>
          <h3 id="agricultural-productivity">Was agricultural productivity the problem?</h3>
          <p>
            Argentine agriculture has been one of the country's most productive sectors. The growth record would look better if the rest of the economy had performed like the farm sector.
          </p>
          <p>
            GM soy, approved in 1996, <a href="https://globalagriculturalproductivity.org/2023-gap-report/latin-america-and-the-caribbean/agricultural-tfp-growth-in-argentina-investments-in-research-and-innovation/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">spread to over 90%</a> of production within five years, faster than in the United States. Today <a href="https://www.yieldgap.org/argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">99% of soy</a> and 95% of corn is transgenic while 90% of cropland is under no-till, among the highest shares on earth. Farm capital stock doubled between 1995 and 2020. Grain and oilseed output roughly tripled from about 40 million tonnes in the early 1990s to records around 140 million, and Argentina became the world's top exporter of soybean meal and oil. The state taxed the sector throughout that expansion.
          </p>
          <p>
            Policy held back an otherwise productive sector. Retenciones took up to 35% of the soy price at the border; during cepo years the overvalued official exchange rate confiscated a further slice, so growers at times kept roughly half the world price. The 2008 attempt to push sliding-scale rates above 40% (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_Argentine_agrarian_strike" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Resolution 125</a>) triggered a four-month farm lockout and died on the vice president's tie-breaking Senate vote. In beef, the <a href="https://quarterraglobal.com/blog/2021/7/8/the-banning-of-argentine-beef-past-present-and-future" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">March 2006 export ban</a> and subsequent quotas knocked Argentina from third-largest exporter (700,000 tonnes in 2005) to eleventh (200,000 tonnes by 2014), while <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40100-016-0070-9" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">the herd shrank</a> by more than 10 million head between 2007 and 2012. Once duties were cut and quotas scrapped under Milei, 2024 exports hit their <a href="https://www.marineinsight.com/shipping-news/argentina-lifts-50-year-ban-on-live-cattle-exports-to-boost-economy/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">highest volume</a> in a century. Wheat plantings fell to multi-decade lows under Kirchner-era export permits. Brazil, which does not tax farm exports, now harvests more than three times Argentina's soybean tonnage; thirty years ago the gap was about two to one.
          </p>
          <p>
            So the "narrow export base" the IMF keeps flagging is not evidence that farming itself was unproductive. It partly reflects how policy constrained the country's most productive tradable sector and how little the protected manufacturing and non-tradable sectors diversified exports.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Sowell's addition.</strong> Milei <a href="https://www.econlib.org/javier-mileis-economic-understanding/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">quotes Thomas Sowell approvingly</a>. Sowell's work on price signals, political incentives, talent allocation and human capital helps explain how the macroeconomic cycle kept reproducing itself.
          </p>
          <h3 id="price-controls-stage-two">Sowell on price controls: stage two</h3>
          <p>
            Sowell's oldest lesson is that a price ceiling delivers stage-one relief and stage-two shortages. Argentina ran the experiment repeatedly. Energy first: the 2002 emergency law froze utility tariffs, investment stopped and a country sitting on world-class <a href="https://www.argentinashale.com/en/production/argentina-regains-a-surplus-in-the-energy-balance/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">shale gas and oil</a> resources became a net energy importer. The energy trade balance stayed negative from 2011 through 2023; the resulting <a href="https://buenosairesherald.com/business/energy/argentina-ends-record-year-in-oil-production-and-energy-surplus-thanks-to-vaca-muerta" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">$4.4 billion deficit</a> in 2022 drained central bank reserves. The cepo arrived in 2011, the same year the energy balance went negative. Once tariffs were unfrozen and Vaca Muerta built out, the sign flipped: a $5.7 billion surplus in 2024, the largest in 18 years, with energy supplying about <a href="https://www.shale24.com/en/oil-and-gas/energy-trade-surplus-kicks-off-2026-cementing-vaca-muertas-export-dominance-n590" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">70% of the surplus</a> in 2025. Housing second: the 2020 rental law mandated three-year peso-denominated leases with formula indexation; <a href="https://reason.com/2024/09/26/rents-fall-and-listings-increase-after-javier-milei-ends-rent-control-in-argentina/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">listings halved</a> while inflation-adjusted rents rose about 140%, and one in seven Buenos Aires homes sat empty. Milei repealed it in the megadecree; within months <a href="https://reason.com/2025/02/08/the-end-of-rent-control-in-argentina/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">supply had roughly tripled</a> while real rents fell by between 27% and 40%. The beef ban above applied the same mechanism to exports.
          </p>
          <h3 id="human-capital-the-original-endowment">Human capital, the original endowment</h3>
          <p>
            Sowell's histories treat human capital as the real wealth of nations; Argentina's founding advantage was exactly that, Sarmiento's schools and mass immigration having made it the best-educated country in Latin America. That endowment is eroding. In <a href="https://www.oecd.org/en/publications/pisa-2022-results-volume-i-and-ii-country-notes_ed6fbcc5-en/argentina_09c7d993-en.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">PISA 2022</a>, Argentine 15-year-olds scored 378 in math against an OECD average of 472; only 27% reached baseline proficiency (a share lower than in 2012), and almost none reached the top levels. Roughly <a href="https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/argentina/government-reacts-to-tough-report-on-secondary-school-crisis-only-10-out-of-100-students-complete-studies.phtml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">one in ten students</a> finishes secondary school on time with adequate language and math. And the capital walks: about <a href="https://www.cato.org/free-society/fall-2025/liberty-versus-power-mileis-argentina" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">1.8 million Argentines</a> have emigrated since 2013, the skilled disproportionately. Stabilization can be decreed in a quarter; rebuilding this takes a generation, which is why it now has its own row in the ranking above.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="fact-check-twelve-claims" aria-labelledby="fact-check-twelve-claims-heading">
          <h2 id="fact-check-twelve-claims-heading">Fact-check: twelve claims at a glance</h2>
          <div class="table-wrap">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="col">Claim</th>
                  <th scope="col">Verdict</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"Argentina's GDP per capita hasn't grown since 1990"</th>
                  <td><strong>False.</strong> Up 57% in PPP terms, but at a third of Chile's pace and with zero net progress after 2011</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"The 1990s market reforms were a complete failure"</th>
                  <td><strong>False.</strong> Hyperinflation ended and growth ran near 6% through 1997; what failed was the fiscal base and the exit strategy</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"The 2001 crisis was caused entirely by fiscal profligacy"</th>
                  <td><strong>Incomplete.</strong> Primary spending's GDP share was roughly flat 1993-2001; provincial deficits, the unfunded pension transition, overvaluation and dollar debt did the killing</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"The IMF caused 2001 through austerity"</th>
                  <td><strong>False, with a caveat.</strong> The vulnerabilities were homegrown, but the Fund financed an unsustainable strategy too long and admits it</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"The fixed exchange rate alone caused 2001"</th>
                  <td><strong>Incomplete.</strong> Lethal only in combination with fiscal weakness, dollarized balance sheets and external shocks</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"An orthodox currency board or dollarization would definitely have prevented it"</th>
                  <td><strong>Unproven counterfactual.</strong> Hanke's factual critique of convertibility is correct; the strong claim is untestable</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"Protectionism explains the whole stagnation"</th>
                  <td><strong>Overstated.</strong> A major productivity and export drag, especially after 2011, but it cannot explain 1998-2002</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"Labor law is Argentina's principal economic problem"</th>
                  <td><strong>Unsupported.</strong> It matters at the margin; macro instability and policy unpredictability dominate</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"Argentina was just unlucky with external shocks"</th>
                  <td><strong>False.</strong> The shocks were triggers; peers hit by the same shocks did not lose a decade</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"Macri failed simply because he reformed too little"</th>
                  <td><strong>Incomplete.</strong> Sequencing was the killer: capital-account opening and dollar borrowing before fiscal credibility, plus an IMF program that misdiagnosed the problem</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"The 1990s privatizations were an unqualified success"</th>
                  <td><strong>Mixed.</strong> Service quality improved dramatically, but corruption and dollar-indexed private monopolies were real costs</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="row">"Milei's poverty collapse is fake" / "is fully real"</th>
                  <td><strong>Real direction, overstated magnitude.</strong> The fall to 28.2% is genuine in INDEC data, but the <a href="https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/argentina/poverty-in-argentina-fell-to-316-in-the-first-half-of-2025-reports-indec.phtml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Buenos Aires Times report</a> notes that self-reported income and outdated consumption baskets flatter the level; child poverty remains above 41%</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="who-benefited-cui-bono" aria-labelledby="who-benefited-cui-bono-heading">
          <h2 id="who-benefited-cui-bono-heading">Who benefited? Cui bono?</h2>
          <p>
            There was no single class that collected every loss. Argentina's errors produced a rotating coalition of winners: politicians who could spend before raising the taxes, provincial machines, favored contractors and regulated firms, borrowers whose debts were rewritten, intermediaries paid on every transaction, households receiving cheap services and people rich enough to move into dollars before each devaluation. Some gains were corrupt, some entirely legal and some were genuine short-term relief for ordinary voters. The durable dividing line was less “the top 0.1% versus everyone else” than <strong>access versus no access</strong>: access to officials, subsidized credit, the official exchange rate, foreign accounts, public employment or a contract whose cost could be passed to future taxpayers.
          </p>
          <h3 id="political-insiders-and-connected-businesses">Political insiders and connected businesses</h3>
          <p>
            Corruption was real, not a slogan. The clearest adjudicated example is the Vialidad case: in 2025 the Supreme Court let stand Cristina Fernández de Kirchner's conviction for fraudulent administration in a scheme that <a href="https://buenosairesherald.com/politics/judiciary/court-demands-key-member-of-case-against-cfks-immediate-detention" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">steered road contracts</a> to companies controlled by Lázaro Báez; Báez was separately convicted of money laundering. Earlier privatizations also created lucrative regulated monopolies and allegations of insider dealing, while later import licenses, public-works awards, energy contracts and preferential exchange rates made official discretion commercially valuable. But proven graft cannot plausibly account for the whole macroeconomic hole. The pension transition alone cost at least 2.7% of GDP annually by 2001, and broad energy and transport subsidies approached 5% of GDP in 2014. Those were bad or unsustainable policies at enormous scale, not money that simply appeared in politicians' personal accounts.
          </p>
          <p>
            Political machines benefited even when no official stole anything. An <a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2102147" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IDB study</a> of Argentine federalism describes many provinces as entrenched local power structures with weak competition, weak checks and clientelistic links; presidents trade discretionary transfers and policy concessions for governors' national support. Public jobs are one currency of that bargain. Between 2011 and 2022, <a href="https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/economy/report-public-employment-up-34-in-argentina-since-2011-private-up-only-3.phtml" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">public payrolls grew 34%</a> while private-sector jobs grew 3%. The employee received a real job, not necessarily a fake one; the governor received an organization dependent on the provincial budget; the bill was nationalized through transfers, debt or inflation. That is patronage, but it is broader than a handful of grifters.
          </p>
          <h3 id="wealthy-savers-and-capital-flight">Wealthy savers and capital flight</h3>
          <p>
            The rich were not uniquely responsible for the crises, but they were uniquely equipped to survive them. A poor household holds pesos and earns a wage adjusted after prices rise; a rich household can own dollars, foreign securities, land or an offshore company. Argentina's 2016 tax amnesty exposed the scale: previously hidden assets equal to <a href="https://taxobservatory.world/publication/revealing-21-of-gdp-in-hidden-assets-evidence-from-argentinas-tax-amnesty/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">21% of GDP</a> were declared, concentrated offshore and among the wealthiest 0.1% of adults. That is strong evidence that the top 0.1% was a major beneficiary of the ability to escape peso depreciation and domestic taxation. It is not evidence that every member obtained the money through corruption, or that all offshore saving was illegal; it shows who possessed the strongest financial shelter.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Macri cycle makes the concentration visible. The central bank's transaction records show that residents accumulated more than $86 billion in foreign assets during 2015-2019 while public debt and portfolio inflows supplied dollars. <a href="https://www.bcra.gob.ar/en/publicaciones/foreign-exchange-market-debt-and-external-asset-formation-report-2015-2019/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Just 100 buyers</a> accounted for $24.7 billion; the top ten for $7.9 billion; the top 1% of corporate buyers for $41.1 billion; and the top 1% of individual buyers for $16.2 billion. The BCRA report was written under Macri's political opponents and its policy interpretation should be read accordingly, but those concentration figures come from the bank's own foreign-exchange records. IMF disbursements did not literally get wired to a list of oligarchs: they replenished fungible reserves while residents and investors exited. Economically, however, public borrowing supplied the foreign currency and the state retained the debt.
          </p>
          <h3 id="large-debtors-banks-and-financial-intermediaries">Large debtors, banks and financial intermediaries</h3>
          <p>
            The sharpest one-off transfer followed the 2001 collapse. Under the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argentine_economic_emergency_law" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2002 economic emergency law</a>, the government converted private dollar loans at one peso per dollar but dollar deposits at 1.4 pesos, plus indexation. Borrowers therefore had part of their real debt erased. Banks were left with the mismatch, so the Treasury issued roughly $10 billion of <a href="https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/109561468768712856/txt/28081.txt" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">BODEN compensation bonds</a>. The final incidence was a taxpayer-financed subsidy to bank borrowers, including highly leveraged large companies. Calling banks the simple winners is wrong: deposit freezes, pesification and default destroyed bank capital and reputation, and the bonds largely compensated a loss imposed by the state. The clearest winners were debtors whose liabilities were converted at the favorable rate; the public inherited the repair bill.
          </p>
          <p>
            Intermediaries nevertheless earned rents during the booms. AFJPs charged fees on mandatory pension contributions; banks, brokers and sophisticated investors earned spreads from high-yield government paper and the <em>bicicleta financiera</em>; firms with import permits or access to the official dollar could capture the gap to the market rate. Blustein's clearest case is the June 2001 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Megacanje" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"><em>megacanje</em></a>: seven banks arranged an exchange of <a href="https://www.fitchratings.com/research/sovereigns/fitch-publishes-report-on-argentine-debt-restructuring-17-10-2001" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">$29.5 billion of bonds</a>, buying temporary payment relief at much higher future cost. The IEO calculated that it reduced 2001–2005 debt service by $12.6 billion but added <a href="https://www.elibrary.imf.org/downloadpdf/display/book/9781589063594/9781589063594.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">$22.1 billion after 2005</a>. Blustein reports $137 million in contracted bank fees, of which about $90 million was paid before default; the IEO independently confirms the swap's adverse arithmetic, though not that fee figure.
          </p>
          <p>
            Yet creditors as a class did not win consistently, and “Wall Street versus Argentina” is too simple. Most bondholders accepting the 2005 restructuring took losses around 70-75%; Argentine banks and pension funds were loaded with defaulted public debt; and foreign utilities suffered pesification and tariff freezes. Nor were all foreign bondholders institutions: roughly 400,000 <a href="https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2004/07/22/to-err-is-human" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Italian retail investors</a> held €14.7 billion when Argentina defaulted, often after banks marketed the bonds as a high-yield alternative to safe domestic debt. A small group of holdouts that bought distressed bonds and litigated did exceptionally well: Argentina finally agreed in 2016 to pay four principal holdout creditors <a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/business/factbox-argentina-and-creditors-settle-historic-sovereign-debt-dispute-idUSKCN0W22O3/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">$4.65 billion</a>. Finance offered repeated opportunities for profit, not a guaranteed one-way transfer to “the banks.”
          </p>
          <h3 id="organized-constituencies-and-ordinary-consumers">Organized constituencies and ordinary consumers</h3>
          <p>
            A much larger group received smaller, visible benefits: public employees, pensioners, protected manufacturers, unionized formal workers and urban households paying frozen electricity, gas and transport fares. These were not imaginary gains. A subsidized bill left more money for food; a protected factory preserved jobs; a pension moratorium gave income to an elderly person without enough recorded contributions. They also formed constituencies that made withdrawal politically costly. The distribution was often badly targeted: the richest fifth received about 23% of electricity subsidies and 37% of network-gas subsidies, versus 16.8% and 8% for <a href="https://documents1.worldbank.org/curated/en/435261471340419978/pdf/107852-WP-P155167-PUBLIC-TheIncidenceofSubsidiesinArgentinaFINAL.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">the poorest fifth</a>, because richer households consumed more and were more likely to have network gas. But the poor still benefited and were hit hard when tariffs caught up. That is why “corrupt elites stole everything” is politically satisfying and analytically incomplete: unsustainable policy survived partly because millions rationally defended their immediate slice.
          </p>
          <h3 id="who-paid-for-the-benefits">Who paid for the benefits?</h3>
          <p>
            The recurring payers were less organized and less able to hedge: workers whose wages were adjusted only after inflation had already cut their purchasing power, cash holders, taxpayers outside favored regimes, exporters forced to sell dollars cheaply, small firms denied imports or credit, bank depositors during freezes and future citizens left with debt and depleted infrastructure. <a href="https://www.bis.org/publ/bppdf/bispap157_b.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">BIS research on Argentina</a> finds inflation weighs disproportionately on poorer households because essentials dominate their budgets and cash is a larger share of their wealth. Wealthy dollar holders may gain in relative terms when the peso falls, but the Treasury is usually inflation's first beneficiary: money creation lets it spend before the price level fully adjusts. The eventual recession destroys income across classes.
          </p>
          <p>
            So the answer is: <strong>yes, corrupt politicians and cronies captured meaningful rents; yes, the top 0.1% had the best escape routes; neither was the sole or even always the largest cash beneficiary.</strong> The system endured because concentrated actors captured large contracts and financial transfers while much broader groups received jobs, cheap services, protected incomes or temporary consumption. Costs were delayed, obscured and dispersed through inflation, taxes, default and lower investment. Half a century of that bargain also redirected talent toward tax engineering, FX arbitrage, lobbying, subsidy management and litigation. <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40503-019-0076-2" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">The institutional evidence</a> is consistent with state-backed favoritism and rent-seeking suppressing productive investment; the political economy explains why the errors recurred after their aggregate cost was obvious.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="would-milei-help" aria-labelledby="would-milei-help-heading">
          <h2 id="would-milei-help-heading">Would Milei help?</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Yes, he already has—but “help” is not the same as “reverse a century of relative decline.”</strong> Milei attacked the most immediate mechanism behind Argentina's repeated collapses: a Treasury that spent more than it could tax and eventually commandeered the central bank. Inflation, the fiscal balance, measured poverty, growth and market access all improved materially by July 2026. His program has therefore raised the probability of a durable recovery. It will be sufficient only if stabilization becomes impersonal institutions and if investment, productivity and exports—not another temporary consumption or carry-trade boom—drive the next decade.
          </p>
          <h3 id="what-milei-promised-and-delivered">What he promised—and delivered</h3>
          <p>
            The central campaign promise was the “chainsaw”: eliminate the deficit, stop money creation and shrink the state. That part was delivered with unusual speed. The primary balance swung from a 2.9%-of-GDP deficit in 2023 to a 1.8% surplus in 2024, with a 0.3% overall surplus, and remained inside the zero-deficit anchor through 2025. Real primary spending fell by roughly 30%, subsidies and discretionary transfers were cut, public works were halted or concessioned and tens of thousands of federal jobs disappeared. The adjustment was socially expensive and leaned initially on compressed pensions, public wages and capital spending, but it was not the “expansionary austerity” gradualism tried under Macri: financing needs were removed first. The central bank stopped direct Treasury financing and transferred much of its interest-bearing peso liability problem to the Treasury, making the fiscal constraint visible.
          </p>
          <p>
            The stabilization results are substantial. Annual inflation fell from 211.4% in 2023 to 31.5% in 2025; the <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2026/english/1argea2026001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">IMF projects</a> about 25% end-of-period inflation and 3.5% growth in 2026. Output grew 4.4% in 2025 after the recession, real incomes recovered and measured poverty fell from 52.9% in the first half of 2024 to roughly 28-29% by late 2025. The poverty level is flattered by an outdated basket and self-reported income, as noted above, but the direction and much of the decline are real. This combination—disinflation, growth and a fiscal surplus—is better than Argentina's previous stabilizations at the same stage.
          </p>
          <p>
            Deregulation also moved beyond rhetoric. Decree 70/2023 and the 2024 Ley Bases removed price, rental, trade and business rules; most personal currency controls and many payment restrictions were lifted in April 2025; the RIGI regime granted 30 years of tax, customs and foreign-exchange stability to large projects. By April 2026, <a href="https://www.mfat.govt.nz/en/trade/mfat-market-reports/argentinas-economic-and-trade-outlook-july-2026" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">14 RIGI projects</a> worth more than $28 billion had been approved, mainly in oil, gas, mining and power. Argentina signed new trade arrangements with the EU, EFTA and United States, reduced some export duties and pursued OECD and CPTPP accession. These commitments help lock openness into treaties rather than a presidential promise.
          </p>
          <p>
            The October 2025 midterms gave Milei a stronger, though not unlimited, congressional base. Congress approved a real 2026 budget and <a href="https://knowledge.dlapiper.com/dlapiperknowledge/globalemploymentlatestdevelopments/2026/argentinas-labor-modernization-bill-top-points" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Law 27,802</a> in March 2026, a broad labor reform that permits hours banks and more flexible contracts, narrows severance calculations and litigation exposure, reduces some payroll contributions and creates employer-funded severance accounts. Whether it produces formal jobs rather than simply weaker protection is empirical and will take years to know, but passing it by statute makes reversal harder than undoing a decree.
          </p>
          <h3 id="what-milei-promised-but-has-not-delivered">What he promised—but has not delivered</h3>
          <p>
            Milei campaigned on <a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2023/11/20/milei-wins-in-argentina-edging-the-country-closer-to-the-us-dollar.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dollarization</a>, closing the central bank and privatizing the pension system. None has happened. The peso and BCRA remain, operating a crawling exchange-rate band; monetary credibility still depends heavily on this government maintaining the fiscal surplus. Most exchange controls were lifted, not all: corporate legacy liabilities and some import and dividend transactions remain managed. Dollarization may have been an unnecessary or impractical promise, but abandoning it means the institutional lock against future monetary financing was not installed.
          </p>
          <p>
            The promised tax revolution is also incomplete. Export taxes were reduced but survive, as do the bank-debit tax, provincial gross-receipts taxes, a 21% VAT and high payroll charges. Argentina still has about 155 levies, seven of which raise almost all revenue, and 44.1% of workers <a href="https://reason.org/commentary/tax-reform-is-essential-to-restore-prosperity-in-argentina/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">remain informal</a>. The government and IMF have a plan to simplify taxes gradually, but as of July 2026 it is mostly a plan. Broad privatization has likewise been slow: Ley Bases authorized eight companies for full or partial sale, but IMPSA was the first completed transaction and major firms remain public. Pension reform is deferred; the <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2026/english/1argea2026001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">current IMF timetable</a> only begins designing it for an end-2027 benchmark.
          </p>
          <h3 id="why-the-program-might-be-enough">Why it might be enough</h3>
          <p>
            Argentina does not need every libertarian campaign promise to grow. A credible prohibition on deficit monetization, competitive exchange rate, simpler tax and labor rules, open imports and stable property rights would address most of the high-weight failures ranked earlier. Energy is already demonstrating the mechanism: investment in Vaca Muerta turned a chronic drain on reserves into an export surplus, while mining and agriculture can widen the dollar-earning base. RIGI commitments are not completed factories, but $28 billion of approved projects is more concrete than a confidence survey. The IMF's baseline has medium-term growth settling near 3%, not an Asian miracle, but sustained 3% growth with lower population growth would reverse the post-2011 decline in per-capita income.
          </p>
          <h3 id="why-it-might-still-fail">Why it might still fail</h3>
          <p>
            The monetary and external flank remains fragile. Argentina missed its 2025 net-reserve target; the IMF estimated net international reserves near negative $10 billion in early 2026. The BCRA then bought more than $10 billion by June, a major improvement, but gross purchases are not the same as freely usable reserves after swaps, IMF obligations and other foreign-currency liabilities. A defended band can again produce overvaluation if inflation outruns depreciation. The IMF still calls Argentina's repayment capacity <a href="https://www.imf.org/-/media/files/publications/cr/2026/english/1argea2026001.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">subject to exceptional risks</a> and assumes continued market access, exchange-rate flexibility and political implementation.
          </p>
          <p>
            The fiscal achievement is real but not fully institutionalized. Some early savings came from allowing pensions and salaries to lag inflation and from nearly stopping infrastructure investment; those cannot fall forever. Aging, provincial finances and the unreformed pension system will push spending upward. Simultaneously cutting distortionary taxes without reopening the deficit requires deeper spending efficiency, a new federal tax bargain and growth broad enough to refill the base. The 2026 labor law may reduce hiring risk, but it cannot by itself formalize workers facing a 35-41% payroll wedge. Education quality, shallow domestic credit and judicial unpredictability also remain largely untouched.
          </p>
          <p>
            Growth is still concentrated. Agriculture benefited from weather, energy from world-class geology and investment incentives, and the 2025 rebound partly reversed the 2024 slump. RIGI's special guarantees may be necessary because ordinary Argentine rules lack credibility, but a country is not institutionally repaired if only projects above $200 million receive 30-year stability. The test is whether small and medium firms invest without bespoke protection, whether non-resource exports diversify and whether private credit rises from roughly 15% of GDP. Otherwise Argentina may stabilize as a volatile commodity exporter without converging on rich-country productivity.
          </p>
          <h3 id="the-milei-verdict-as-of-july-2026">The verdict as of July 2026</h3>
          <p>
            Milei has delivered the necessary first half of a turnaround and more structural reform than his congressional weakness initially suggested. He has not yet delivered the second half: a tax system compatible with formality, solvent pensions, deep peso finance, robust reserves and rules that a successor cannot casually reverse. Watch five tests: the fiscal anchor surviving the 2027 election; net reserves becoming unambiguously positive without a badly overvalued peso; tax and pension reform passing through Congress; investment spreading beyond specially protected megaprojects; and exports and productivity rising for several years. Passing those tests would make a durable reversal likely. Until then, the evidence supports <strong>successful stabilization with a credible route to recovery</strong>, not a completed Argentine economic miracle.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="the-synthesis" aria-labelledby="the-synthesis-heading">
          <h2 id="the-synthesis-heading">The synthesis</h2>
          <p>
            Argentina repeatedly borrowed credibility instead of earning it. Convertibility borrowed it from dollar reserves; the Kirchners borrowed time from exporters and peso savers; Macri borrowed dollars. Each arrangement ended when its financing did. Milei has built more credibility at home by removing the fiscal deficit before fully liberalizing, which makes this attempt structurally stronger. It becomes a historical break only when the rules survive him. Until then, call it stabilization with a plausible route to convergence—not convergence itself.
          </p>
        </section>
      </article>
    </main>

